  <li><a href="#stumpmast">STUMPMAST (or STUMP MAST)</a></li>
</ul>
<hr />
  <dl style="margin-left: 2 em">
  	<dd><a name="stella"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STELLA</dt>
  <dd>The Latin/Italian for star and occasionally seen in place of that term &ndash; see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs6.html#star">star 1)</a>&rsquo;.</dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="stepped"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STEPPED</dt>
  <dd>The term used when the diagonal dividing line on a shield, banner of arms or a flag is 
  created by a series of step-like indentations &ndash; but see the note below (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-d.html#dancetty">dancetty</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs2.html#serrated">serrated 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvsb.html#steppedfly">stepped fly</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvsb.html#steppedgonfalon">stepped gonfalon</a>&rsquo;).<p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2070.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2070.gif" alt="[stepped example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2070a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2070a.gif" alt="[stepped example]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag and Arms of <a href="hr-kr-ds.html">Donja Stubica</a>, Croatia (fotw)</em>
  <p><em>Please note that this term may also be used to describe other charges as appropriate, for example a �mount stepped� 
  (as illustrated below), or see the &quot;stepped pattern&quot; on the flag of 
  <a href="az-artsa.html">Artsakh</a> &ndash; see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm4.html#mount">mount</a>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcs.html#crossofcalvary">cross of Calvary</a>&rsquo;).
  </em>
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3044.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3044.gif" alt="[stepped example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;
  <br>
  <em>Flag of <a href="pt-vlpag.html">Argeriz</a>, Portugal (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="steppedfly"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STEPPED FLY</dt>
  <dd>1) (adj) A term for the type of flag, now largely (if not wholly) obsolete, whose fly is 
  extended by a rectangular projection (smaller in width and of varying length) centred on the 
  horizontal meridian of the flag (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve1.html#engrailedfly">engrailed fly</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf5.html#fly">fly 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm2.html#meridian">meridian</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvsb.html#stepped">stepped</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs1.html#schwenkel">schwenkel</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="#stepped">stepped</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-t.html#tail">tails</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>2) See &lsquo;<a href="#steppedgonfalon">stepped gonfalon</a>&rsquo; below.
    <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d314b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d314b.gif" alt="[stepped flags]" border="0" width="213" height="107"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d314.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d314.gif" alt="[stepped flags]" border="0" width="159" height="107"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d314a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d314a.gif" alt="[stepped flags]" border="0" width="166" height="107"></a>
  <br /><em>A selection of 19th Century US House Flags (CS)</em><p><em>Notes<br>
  a) This was not considered an established term and had been 
  introduced by the Editors as no (accurately descriptive) established alternative could then be found, 
  however, since that time the Italian term &ldquo;gonfaloni scalinati&rdquo; has been discovered and is accordingly 
  defined below.<br>b) At the time of writing it is unclear as to whether the flag having a straight-sided but angled fly (as illustrated below) should be considered as �engrailed� or �stepped� � see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve1.html#engrailedfly">engrailed fly</a>&rsquo;.
	</em> 
	<p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1528.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1528.gif" alt="Betxi, Spain" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag of Betxi, Spain (Jose Antonio Jimenez Ruiz)</em>
	</dd>
	
    </dd>
  <hr/><a name="steppedgonfalon"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STEPPED GONFALON</dt>
  <dd>(adj) The term (and a direct translation of the Italian &ldquo;gonfaloni scalinati&rdquo;) that may be used to 
  describe those gonfalons whose fly forms a series of steps as in the examples given below (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg2.html#gonfalon">gonfalon</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="#stepped">stepped</a>&rsquo; ).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d716.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d716.gif" alt="stepped gonfalons" border="0" width="433" height="197"></a>
  <br /><em>Asymmetric Right (or Dexter) Stepped; Asymmetric Left (or Sinister) Stepped; Symmetrical Outwardly Stepped; Symmetrical 
  Inwardly Stepped</em></dd>

  <hr /><a name="stickpin"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STICKPIN (or STICK PIN) FLAG</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#lapelflag">lapel flag 1)</a>&rsquo;.<p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d899b.jpg">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d899b.jpg" alt="[flag pin]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em>Stickpin flag (worldflags4u)</em></dd>
 
  <hr /><a name="stoned"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STONED</dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-g.html#gemmed">gemmed 1)</a>&rsquo;.<p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2971.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2971.gif" alt="[stoned]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em>Flag of <a href="ch-fr227.html">Villarsel-le-Gibloux</a>, 
  Switzerland (fotw)</em></dd>
 
  <hr /><a name="stormflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STORM FLAG (or ENSIGN) </dt>
  <dd>1) Specifically, in US military usage, the smallest size of national flag flown at army 
  and marine corps 
  posts - 5 feet (1.5 m) wide by 9 feet 6 inches (2.9 m) long, or half as wide and 
  half as long as a marine corps post flag (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-g.html#garrisonflag">garrison flag</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp5.html#postflag">post flag</a>&rsquo;). </dd>
  <dd>2) Generally, a smaller size of flag than that laid down for general use, and meant to 
  be flown in stormy weather. </dd>
  <dd>3) See &lsquo;<a href="#stormwarning">storm warning flag</a>&rsquo; below. </dd>
  <hr /><a name="stormwarning"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STORM WARNING FLAG (or PENNANT) </dt>
  <dd>In US and some other usage, one of a system of flags and pennants used to 
  warn mariners of severe weather in the area - a weather or weather warning 
  flag (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb4.html#beachflag">beach flag</a>&rsquo; and �<a href="vxt-dvm1.html#maritimelifesavingflag">maritime lifesaving flags</a>�).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d176a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d176a.gif" alt="Storm warning flag" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d176b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d176b.gif" alt="Storm warning flag" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br />
  <em>US Coast Guard <a href="us-storm.html">Hurricane Warning Flag</a> and
  <a href="us-storm.html">Gale Warning Pennant</a> (fotw)</em>
  <hr /><a name="streamer"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STREAMER </dt>
  <dd>1) A long narrow ribbon attached to a flag&rsquo;s staff, such as those upon which 
  battle honours are inscribed - see �<a href="vxt-dva9.html#awardstreamer">award streamer</a>� 
  (also �<a href="vxt-dv-b.html#banderole">banderole</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb3.html#battlehonor">battle honour</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="#streamerretainingring">streamer retaining ring</a>&rsquo;). </dd>
  <dd>2) The term for a long narrow flag or pennant, now obsolete, usually (but not invariably) 
  showing livery colours, often fitted with a frame at the head and flown from a vessel for reasons of bravado or as decoration &ndash; sometimes (inaccurately) called a gonfalon (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva3.html#ancient">ancient 2)</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-d.html#deckflags">deck flags</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf8.html#frame">frame 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvl2.html#liverycolors">livery colours</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm1.html#mastheadpennant">masthead pennant 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm2.html#merchantpendant">merchant pendant</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp1.html#pavisade">pavisade</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp2.html#pennant">pennant 2)</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp5.html#postures">postures</a>&rsquo;.
  <br />3) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvw2.html#wimpel">wimpel</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d896.jpg">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d896.jpg" alt="[streamers]" border="0" width="140" height="105"></a>&nbsp; 
    <a href="../images/v/vxt-d897.jpg">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d897.jpg" alt="[streamers]" border="0" width="142" height="102"></a>&nbsp; 
    <a href="../images/v/vxt-d898.jpg">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d898.jpg" alt="[streamers]" border="0" width="167" height="104"></a> <br />
    <em>The Henri Grace a Dieu, The Peter and The Salamander, English Royal Navy c1525 (Wikipedia)
    <p>
    Please note with regard to 2) that streamers supplied to the Henry Grace a Dieu (flagship of the English royal fleet) in 1514 are recorded as having ranged between 15 and 51 yards (13.5m and 46m) long.
    </em>
    </dd>
    
  <hr /><a name="streamerretainingring"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STREAMER RETAINING RING </dt>
  <dd>An often decorative, ridged band sometimes fitted to the staff of a military 
  colour below the finial, and from which battle streamers are suspended (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb3.html#battlehonor">battle honour</a>, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#color">colour 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs6.html#staff">staff 2)</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="#streamer">streamer 1)</a>&rsquo;). </dd>
  <hr /><a name="strike"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STRIKE (or STRIKE ONE&rsquo;S COLOURS/COLORS)</dt>
  <dd>(v) Nautical terms meaning to surrender - to lower or haul down 
  one's flag, as a sign of that surrender (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb3.html#battleensign">battle ensign(s)</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#colors">colours 4)</a>&rsquo;  
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-n.html#nailingcolours">nail one&rsquo;s colours to the mast</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4191.jpg">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4191.jpg" alt="strike colours" border="0" height="162" width="108"></a><br> 
  <em>French Frigate Striking Her Colours 1778 (Wikipedia)</em></dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="stringed"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STRINGED</dt>
  <dd>In heraldry a term used when the strings of a bow or of a musical instrument, the carrying strap of a horn, or the tapes that hang below a prelate&rsquo;s mitre, particularly when these are of a different tincture 
  (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb8.html#buglehorn">bugle horn</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc9.html#crozier">crozier</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-g.html#garnished">garnished</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#lappets">lappets</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm3.html#mitre">mitre</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt1.html#tincture">tincture</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2915.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2915.gif" alt="stringed" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4420.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4420.gif" alt="stringed" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4421.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4421.gif" alt="stringed" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br />
  <em>Flag of 
  <a href="es-gi-ct.html">Cornell� del Terri</a>, Spain (fotw); 
  Arms of <a href="pt-brgvf.html">Vila�a e Fradelos</a>, Portugal (fotw); 
  Flag of Admiral of the <a href="ie~yrcyc.html#adm">Royal Cork Yacht Club</a>, Ireland (fotw) </em>
  
  <hr /><a name="stripe"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STRIPE(S)</dt>
  <dd>A band or bands of colour &ndash; whether disposed vertically, horizontally or 
  diagonally &ndash; which generally reach one or more edges of a flag, but which do 
  not cover the whole area &ndash; see &lsquo;<a href="#striped">striped</a>&rsquo; 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt!dv-9.html">appendix IX</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb2.html#bar">bar</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb5.html#bend">bend</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc7.html#convergingstripes">converging stripes</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve4.html#expandingstripes">expanding stripe(s)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf1.html#fess">fess</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm5.html#multistripe">multi-stripe</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-p.html#pale">pale</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt5.html#triband">triband</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt5.html#tricolor">tricolour</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb5.html#beicolor">bicolour</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d329d.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d329d.gif" alt="St.Vincent" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2760.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2760.gif" alt="Gabon" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1591.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1591.gif" alt="Mauritius" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br /><em>National Flag of <a href="vc.html">St. Vincent</a> (fotw); National Flag 
  of 
  <a href="ga.html">Gabon</a> (fotw); National Flag of 
  <a href="mu.html">Mauritius</a> (fotw)</em><hr/><a name="striped"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STRIPED</dt>
  <dd>The term used to describe a flag having more than two parallel bands of colour &ndash; whether 
  disposed vertically, horizontally or diagonally &ndash; but see &lsquo;<a href="vxt!dv-9.html">appendix IX</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc7.html#convergingstripes">converging stripes</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve4.html#expandingstripes">expanding stripe(s)</a>&rsquo;,&nbsp; 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm5.html#multistripe">multi-stripe</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="#stripe">stripe</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt5.html#triband">triband</a>&rsquo;, and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt5.html#tricolor">tricolour</a>&rsquo; (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb5.html#bicolor">bicolour</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1593.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1593.gif" alt="Belgium civil flag" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2761.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2761.gif" alt="Germany" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1594.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1594.gif" alt="Uganda" border="0" height="108"></a><br />
  <em>Civil Flag of <a href="be~civ.html">Belgium</a> (fotw); National Flag of 
  <a href="de.html">Germany</a> (fotw); National Flag of 
  <a href="ug.html">Uganda</a> (fotw)</em></dd>

  <hr /><a name="stumpmast"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">STUMPMAST (or STUMP MAST)</dt>
  <dd>A truncated mast (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf5.html#flyingline">flying line</a>&rsquo;, 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm1.html#mast">mast 1)</a>&rsquo;).
  <p><em>Please note that a stumpmast with a fixed yard at the 
  truck giving it a T-shape is common right forward in the bows of those bulk cargo 
  carrying vessels plying the inland waterways of Europe so as to allow for passing 
  under bridges and other overhead obstructions.  The taller of this type of mast is 
  also often hinged for lowering to deck level for the same purpose  (see also 
  '<a href="vxt-dvt6.html#truck">truck</a>' and 
  '<a href="vxt-dv-y.html#yard">yard</a>').</em>

</dl>
